<section>
    @* ITM's evolution to the current state *@
    <article>
        <h2>
            ITM's evolution to the current state
        </h2>
        <p>
            Information Technology Management (ITM) plays a crucial role in todayâ€™s digital world. ITM involves the
            planning, organizing, and controlling of IT resources to achieve organizational goals.In this blog, we will
            explore ITM's evolution to the current state and its future prospects.
        </p>
        <p>
            ITM has evolved over time as technology became more advanced and pervasive in every aspect of business. Here
            are some of the key stages in the evolution of ITM:
        <section>
                @* EDP *@
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-sm">
                    <p>
                        <b>
                            1950-1960: Electronic Data Processing (EDP):
                        </b>
                        This was the first stage of using large-scale computer systems to process and store data and
                        transactions, such as
                        <b>
                            cash deposits, payment orders, and inventory records
                        </b>. EDP systems improved the
                        speed and efficiency of data processing and record-keeping.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm py-5">
                    <img src="https://itchronicles.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Information-technology-evolution.png.webp"
                        alt="Computing Goes Mainstream with Mainframes (Image source: Forbes)" class="img-fluid rounded"
                        loading="lazy">
                </div>
            </div>
                @* MIS *@
            <div>
                <p>
                    <b>
                        1960-1970: Management Information Systems (MIS):
                    </b>
                    This was the stage when computer systems were able to generate reports from the data they collected,
                    such as
                    <b>
                        sales analysis, cost trends, production performance, etc
                    </b>. MIS systems helped managers to
                    evaluate the information and make better decisions.
                </p>
            </div>
                @* DSS *@
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-sm">
                    <p>
                        <b>
                            1970-1980: Decision Support Systems (DSS):
                        </b>
                        his was the stage when computer systems were able to provide historical and ad hoc reports on
                        both
                        internal and external information, such as market pricing, risk analysis, sales forecasting,
                        etc.
                        DSS
                        systems enabled managers to make more strategic and complex decisions. This was also the era
                        when
                        <i>
                            <b>
                                personal computers (PCs)
                            </b>
                        </i> entered the workplace and connected to the main server, making information more accessible
                        to
                        employees.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-sm py-5">
                    <img src="https://itchronicles.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/IT-eveolution-personal-computer.png.webp"
                        alt="personal computers (PCs) (Image source: Wikipedia)" class="img-fluid rounded">
                </div>
            </div>
                @* EIS *@
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-sm">
                    <p>
                        <b>
                            1980-1990: Executive Information Systems (EIS):
                        </b>
                        This was the stage when PCs allowed executives to purchase software tailored to their
                        department's
                        needs, such as <b>
                            accounting, project management, HR systems, etc.
                        </b> EIS systems allowed executives to access
                        and analyse information from different sources and perspectives
                        .This was also the era when networking technologies enabled communication and collaboration
                        among
                        different locations and organization.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="pb-5">
                    <img src="https://itchronicles.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/It-evolution-networking.png.webp"
                        alt="Networking the PC through the Client-server and Enterprise Computing Eras (Image source: IBM)"
                        class="img-fluid rounded" loading="lazy">
                </div>

            </div>
                @* ERP *@
            <div>
                <p>
                    <b>
                        1990-2000: Enterprise Resource Management (ERP) Systems:
                    </b>
                    This was the stage when software systems integrated all the business processes and functions into a
                    single system, such as <b>
                        finance, manufacturing, sales, distribution, etc.
                    </b> ERP systems streamlined and
                    standardized the business operations and data across the organization. This was also the era when
                    internet technologies enabled e-commerce and online services
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>
        </p>
    </article>
